\\section\{Introduction\}\par
\par
Many authors submitting to journals now use \\LaTeXe\\ to prepare their papers.\par
This paper describes the \\textsf\{oupau.cls\} class file that can be used to convert\par
articles produced with other \\LaTeXe\\ class files into the correct form for\par
publication in the \\textit\{Oxford University Press Ltd Journal\}.\par
\par
The \\textsf\{oupau.cls\} class file preserves much of the standard\par
\\LaTeXe\\ interface so that any document that was produced using the\par
standard \\LaTeXe\\ \\textsf\{article\} style can easily be converted to\par
work with the \\textsf\{oupau\} style. However, the width of text and\par
type size will vary from that of \\textsf\{article.cls\}; therefore,\par
\\textit\{line breaks will change\} and it is likely that displayed\par
mathematics and tabular material will need re-setting.\par
\par
In the following sections we describe how to lay out your code to use \\textsf\{oupau.cls\}\par
to reproduce the \\textit\{article\}. However, this paper is not a guide to using\par
\\LaTeXe\\ and we would refer you to any of the many books available\par
(see, for example, \\cite\{Kopka_Daly:2003,Lamport:1994,Mittelbach_Goossens:2004\}).\par
\par
\par
\\section\{The Three Golden Rules\}\par
\par
Before we proceed, we would like to stress \\textit\{three golden rules\} that need\par
to be followed to enable the most efficient use of your code at the typesetting stage:\par
\\begin\{itemize\}\par
\\item[(i)]\par
keep your own macros to an absolute minimum;\par
\\item[(ii)]\par
as \\TeX\\ is designed to make sensible spacing decisions by itself, do \\textit\{not\}\par
use explicit horizontal or vertical spacing commands, except in a few accepted\par
(mostly mathematical) situations, such as \\verb"\\," before a\par
differential d, or \\verb"\\quad" to separate an equation from its qualifier.\par
\\end\{itemize\}\par
\par
\par
\\section\{Getting Started\}\par
\par
The \\textsf\{oupau\} class file should run on any standard \\LaTeXe\\ installation.\par
If any of the fonts, class files or packages it requires are missing from your\par
installation, they can be found on the \\textit\{\\TeX\}\\ \\textit\{Live\} CD-ROMs or from CTAN.\par
\par
The \\textit\{Journal\} is published using Times fonts and this is achieved by using\par
the \\textsf\{times\} option as \\verb"\\documentclass[times]\{oupau\}". If for any reason\par
you have a problem using Times you can easily resort to Computer Modern fonts by\par
removing the \\textsf\{times\} option.\par
\par
