\\subsection\{Remarks\}\par
\par
\\begin\{itemize\}\par
\\item[(i)] In \\verb"\\shorttitle", keep the short title to no more than 50 characters.\par
\\item[(ii)] For the abbreviated author lists \\verb"\\abbrevauthor" (for the running headers)\par
and \\verb"\\headabbrevauthor" (for the first page header), use `\\textit\{et al.\}'\par
if there are three or more authors.\par
\\item[(iii)] Note the use of \\verb"\\affil" and \\verb"\\affilnum" to link names and\par
addresses. The address and/or email address of the author for\par
correspondence is defined by \\verb"\\correspdetails".\par
\\item[(iv)] For submitting a double-spaced manuscript, add \\textsf\{doublespace\}\par
as an option to the \\textsf\{documentclass\} line.\par
\\end\{itemize\}\par
\par
\par
\\section\{The Body of the Article\}\par
\par
\\subsection\{Heading levels\}\par
\par
There are three main levels of heading: section, subsection\par
and subsubsection, also known as A, B and C heads\par
and generated by their corresponding \\LaTeX\\ commands, i.e. \\verb"\\section",\par
\\verb"\\subsection" and \\verb"\\subsubsection". You may also need paragraph\par
and subparagraph headings, but consider using a list environment for separating\par
smaller amounts of material. Capitalize all main words (nouns, names, etc.) in\par
the section headings, and only the first word (and any proper nouns of course)\par
in subsection and all lower headings.\par
\par
\par
\\subsection\{Lists\}\par
\par
Lists may be an appropriate alternative to using headings below the level\par
of subsubsection. If the items in the list are complete or near complete sentences,\par
they should each begin with capital letters and end with a full\par
stop. If they are short phrases they should start with a lower case letter and\par
end with a semicolon. Single items need no punctuation or capitals. The final item\par
in any list should end with a full stop. If punctuation is used to introduce the\par
list, use a colon.\par
\par
There are two main ways of presenting a list: numbered and unnumbered.\par
\par
\\subsubsection\{Numbered lists\}\par
\par
Use a numbered list if the order of the items is important, with either roman\par
numerals or lower case letters, both in parentheses. This style helps distinguish\par
such items from heading levels. Numbered lists can be created using the optional\par
argument in square brackets for \\verb"\\item":\par
\\begin\{verbatim\}\par
\\begin\{itemize\}\par
\\item[(i)]\par
...\par
\\item[(ii)]\par
...\par
\\item[(iii)]\par
...\par
\\item[(iv)]\par
...\par
\\item[(v)]\par
...\par
\\end\{itemize\}\par
\\end\{verbatim\}\par
\par
If the order of the list is unimportant, use a bulleted list, which is similar\par
to the above example, except here there is no need for the optional argument in\par
square brackets:\par
\\begin\{verbatim\}\par
\\begin\{itemize\}\par
\\item\par
...\par
\\item\par
...\par
\\item\par
...\par
\\item\par
...\par
\\item\par
...\par
\\end\{itemize\}\par
\\end\{verbatim\}\par
Where necessary, lists may be nested, i.e. use an itemize environment within\par
another itemize environment, as follows:\par
\\begin\{itemize\}\par
\\item[(1)]\par
...\par
\\begin\{itemize\}\par
\\item[(a)]\par
...\par
\\item[(b)]\par
...\par
\\end\{itemize\}\par
\\item[(2)]\par
...\par
\\end\{itemize\}\par
\par
\par
\\subsection\{Theorem-like environments\}\par
\par
These are set as follows:\par
\\begin\{theorem\}\par
\\label\{thm1\}\par
If B equals the Lebesgue measure, then for any measurable function,\par
$\\psi : R_+ \\to  R$, $E_\{\\psi\} \\left( Q(0) \\right) =\par
\\left( 1 - a \\right) \\psi (0)$, with the understanding that the fraction in the\par
right-hand side equals $\\psi (Q(0))$ on the event\par
$\\left\\\{ Q(0) = Q.(0) \\right\\\}$.\par
\\end\{theorem\}\par
\par
This formatting is achieved using\par
\\begin\{verbatim\}\par
\\begin\{theorem\}\par
\\label\{thm1\}\par
...\par
\\end\{theorem\}\par
\\end\{verbatim\}\par
Note the use of the \\LaTeX\\ \\verb"\\label" command. References to this theorem\par
will then take the form, \\verb"Theorem~\\ref\{thm1\}", and will be automatically\par
renumbered if the order changes.\par
\par
For definitions, examples, etc., again use the corresponding \\LaTeX\\ environment\par
(i.e. \\verb"\\begin\{definition\}...\\end\{definition\}", etc.). Proofs are set in a similar way:\par
\\begin\{verbatim\}\par
\\begin\{proof\}\par
...\par
\\end\{proof\}\par
\\end\{verbatim\}\par
For example:\par
\\begin\{proof\}\par
Use $K_\{\\lambda\} > S_\{\\lambda\}$ to translate combinators into $\\lambda$ terms.\par
For the converse, translate $\\lambda x \\ldots$ by $[x < y] \\ldots$\par
and use induction and the lemma.\par
\\end\{proof\}\par
\par
\par
\\subsection\{Mathematics\}\par
\par
\\textsf\{oupau.cls\} makes the full functionality of \\AmSTeX\\ available. We encourage\par
the use of the \\textsf\{align\}, \\textsf\{gather\} and \\textsf\{multline\} environments\par
for displayed mathematics.\par
\par
\par
\\subsection\{Figures and tables\}\par
\par
\\textsf\{oupau.cls\} uses the \\textsf\{graphicx\} package for handling figures.\par
\par
Figures are called in as follows:\par
\\begin\{verbatim\}\par
\\begin\{figure\}\par
\\centering\par
\\includegraphics\{<figure name>\}\par
\\caption\{<Figure caption>\}\par
\\label\{<Figure label>\}\par
\\end\{figure\}\par
\\end\{verbatim\}\par
\par
For further details on how to size figures, etc., with the \\textsf\{graphicx\} package\par
see, for example, \\cite\{Kopka_Daly:2003,Mittelbach_Goossens:2004\}. If figures are\par
available in an acceptable format (for example, .eps, .ps) then they will be used\par
but a printed version should always be provided.\par
\par
The standard coding for a table is shown in Figure~\\ref\{figure: table example\}.\par
